# This file is for learning regular expressions with 'grep'.
# For most regular expression features, it's recommended to use 'grep -E' (for extended regex).

# --- 1. Literal Matching ---
# Search for exact strings.
apple banana orange
applepie
pineapple
banana_split

# --- 2. Anchors (^ and $) ---
# '^' matches the beginning of a line.
# '$' matches the end of a line.
^start_of_line
This is the end$
Another line that ends$

# --- 3. Quantifiers (?, *, +, {n}, {n,}, {n,m}) ---
# '?' matches zero or one occurrence of the preceding character/group.
# '*' matches zero or more occurrences.
# '+' matches one or more occurrences.
# '{n}' matches exactly n occurrences.
# '{n,}' matches n or more occurrences.
# '{n,m}' matches between n and m occurrences.

colou?r (matches color and colour)
Err Error Errror Errorr (try 'Err+or' or 'Err?or')
a*b (matches b, ab, aab, aaab)
a+b (matches ab, aab, aaab)
x.*y (matches x followed by anything, then y)
Phone number: 123-456-7890 (try '[0-9]{3}-[0-9]{3}-[0-9]{4}')
Item ID: ABC-1234 (try '[A-Z]{3}-[0-9]{4}')

# --- 4. Character Classes ---
# '.' matches any single character (except newline).
# '[abc]' matches any one of the characters a, b, or c.
# '[^abc]' matches any character NOT a, b, or c.
# '[a-z]' matches any lowercase letter.
# '[0-9]' matches any digit.
# '[:alnum:]' (alphanumeric), '[:alpha:]' (alphabetic), '[:digit:]' (digits), '[:space:]' (whitespace)

The quick brown fox jumps over the lazy dog.
12345 test @#$!
email@example.com (try '\w+@\w+\.\w+')
   leading and trailing spaces   (try '\s+')
price $100 (try '\$[0-9]+')

# --- 5. Alternation (|) ---
# '|' acts as an OR operator.
cat|dog (matches 'cat' or 'dog')
(apple|orange) juice

# --- 6. Grouping (()) ---
# Group characters to apply quantifiers or alternation to them.
(ab)+c (matches abc, ababc, abababc...)
